    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-01T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-01T20:00:00-05:00" n="784"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d784">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6525: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hong Kong</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Southard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hong Kong</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-02T09:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 2, 1937—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 2—7:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to my telegram of October 18,4 p.m., shipments of Chinese silver from
                    Hong Kong to London are continuing as reported in <pb facs="0635" n="627"
                        xml:id="pg_627"/> the telegram under reference and it is reliably estimated
                    that all stocks of such silver will have left Hong Kong by January 15th.</p>
                <p>During the past 6 weeks Chinese Government silver to the value of approximately
                    20 million Hong Kong dollars has arrived in Hong Kong.</p>
                <p>Repeated to the Ambassador at Hankow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Southard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
